<b>David Hirst</b> (born 1936) is a veteran <system wordnetid="108435388" confidence="0.8">
<economy wordnetid="108366753" confidence="0.8">
<group wordnetid="100031264" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../323/19323.xml">
Middle East</link></group>
</economy>
</system>
 <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../094/511094.xml">
correspondent</link> based in <village wordnetid="108672738" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../428/37428.xml">
Beirut</link></village>
.  He attended <school wordnetid="108276720" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../551/49551.xml">
Rugby School</link></school>
 from 1949 to 1954 and performed his national service in <country wordnetid="108544813" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../628/8087628.xml">
Egypt</link></country>
 and <body wordnetid="107965085" confidence="0.8">
<system wordnetid="108435388" confidence="0.8">
<social_group wordnetid="107950920" confidence="0.8">
<political_orientation wordnetid="106212839" confidence="0.8">
<colony wordnetid="108374049" confidence="0.8">
<economy wordnetid="108366753" confidence="0.8">
<group wordnetid="100031264" confidence="0.8">
<democracy wordnetid="106217103" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../593/5593.xml">
Cyprus</link></democracy>
</group>
</economy>
</colony>
</political_orientation>
</social_group>
</system>
</body>
 from 1954 to 1956. From 1956 to 1963 he studied at <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../797/31797.xml">
Oxford University</link> and the <university wordnetid="108286163" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../969/470969.xml">
American University of Beirut</link></university>
.  He reported for <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../515/19344515.xml">
the Guardian</link> from 1963 to 1997 and has also written for the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../687/227687.xml">
Christian Science Monitor</link>, the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../378/147378.xml">
Irish Times</link>, the <newspaper wordnetid="106267145" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../769/1071769.xml">
St. Petersburg Times</link></newspaper>
, <newspaper wordnetid="106267145" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../104/639104.xml">
Newsday</link></newspaper>
, the <newspaper wordnetid="106267145" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../442/319442.xml">
San Francisco Chronicle</link></newspaper>
 and the <print_media wordnetid="106263609" confidence="0.8">
<press wordnetid="106263369" confidence="0.8">
<artifact wordnetid="100021939" confidence="0.8">
<instrumentality wordnetid="103575240" confidence="0.8">
<medium wordnetid="106254669" confidence="0.8">
<newspaper wordnetid="106267145" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../004/4015004.xml">
Daily Star</link></newspaper>
</medium>
</instrumentality>
</artifact>
</press>
</print_media>
. He was kidnapped twice and was banned at various times from visiting six Arab countries, including <country wordnetid="108544813" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../628/8087628.xml">
Egypt</link></country>
, <country wordnetid="108544813" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../849/7515849.xml">
Syria</link></country>
, <country wordnetid="108544813" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../303/349303.xml">
Saudi Arabia</link></country>
 and <country wordnetid="108544813" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../928/7515928.xml">
Iraq</link></country>
. He continues to contribute to the Guardian and to other newspapers around the world.
